f the win32s libraries. you've probably" b' heard about win32s, it is a 32-bit windows library that provides' b' much of the windows nt functionality (no support for threads and' b' multitasking and such) but can be run under windows b'' b'' b' i also have mb of ram, and indeed mathcad insisted on a permanent' b' swapfile; it would not run otherwise.' b'' b'' b' mathcad absolutely requires 4mb ram (with 12mb swap file) or 8mb ram' b' (with 8mb swap file). it will give you a not enough memory error if the' b' swap file is less than 8mb. it is a major resource hog. if you do not' b' load the symbolic processor or the smart math, it takes about 5mb of ram' b' (real or virtual) just to load (again, due to the win32s libraries.' b'' b'********************************************************************************' b'* b"* so it seems that in addition to the system requirements shown on mathsoft's b'* advertisement for that you need a swap file, possibly as big as 12mb. b'* looks like i would just need an 8mb swap file, and would need to choose (or b'* can i?) between a faster permanent swap file, or a slower temporary swap file*' b'* b'* apparently a win32 subsystem ships with mathcad how much disk space b'* does this require? b'* b'********************************************************************************' b'' b'i also received these answers:' b'' b'' b" if you've got megs of ram, why not configure 10megs as a ram disk for" b' mathcad? dos permits different bootup configurations.' b'' b'********************************************************************************' b'* b'* can mathcad win32 be configured to use such a ram drive instead of a b"* swap file? if not, i don't see how using dos for an alternate bootup b'* would provide windows with this swap file. some time back i remember a b'* discussion about the issues of using a ram drive to support a swap file, b'* but i thought this involved slower, 8mb systems. b'* b'* i have dos but for various reasons have 